      "raw": "val find_all_good_indices_array (nums: array int) (k: int) : array int",
      "function_name": "find_all_good_indices_array",
      "parameters": [
        {
          "name": "nums",
          "why3_type": "array int",
          "semantic_type": "int_sequence"
        },
        {
          "name": "k",
          "why3_type": "int",
          "semantic_type": "int"
        }
      ],
      "return": {
        "why3_type": "array int",
        "semantic_type": "int_sequence"
      }
    }
  },
  "problem": {
    "description": "You are given a 0-indexed integer array nums of size n and a positive integer k.\nWe call an index i in the range k <= i < n - k good if the following conditions are satisfied:\n\nThe k elements that are just before the index i are in non-increasing order.\nThe k elements that are just after the index i are in non-decreasing order.\n\nReturn an array of all good indices sorted in increasing order.\n \nExample 1:\n\nInput: nums = [2,1,1,1,3,4,1], k = 2\nOutput: [2,3]\nExplanation: There are two good indices in the array:\n- Index 2. The subarray [2,1] is in non-increasing order, and the subarray [1,3] is in non-decreasing order.\n- Index 3. The subarray [1,1] is in non-increasing order, and the subarray [3,4] is in non-decreasing order.\nNote that the index 4 is not good because [4,1] is not non-decreasing.\nExample 2:\n\nInput: nums = [2,1,1,2], k = 2\nOutput: []\nExplanation: There are no good indices in this array.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nn == nums.length\n3 <= n <= 105\n1 <= nums[i] <= 106\n1 <= k <= n / 2\n\n"
  },
